f the laryngeal theory which can be read without specialist knowledge. Research into the Germanic languages has not previously taken account of laryngeal theory, but with it many a sound law, etymology and morphological development can be reformulated or made more precise.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aGerman languagexMorphology. 0aGerman languagexPhonology. 4aEtymologie. 4aGermanische Völker /Sprache. 4aHistorische Phonologie. 4aLaryngal. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aGermanic Peoples / Language.  aHistorical Phonology.  aLaryngeal.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Linguistics and Semiotics 2000 - 2014z9783110636970oZDB-23-DLS08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK GESAMTPAKET / COMPLETE PACKAGE 2007z9783110277135oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PAKET LINGUISTIK UND LITERATURWISSENSCHAFT  2007z9783110276909oZDB-23-DGA0 cprintz978311019604740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311095817140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110958171423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110958171/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LS  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DGAb2007  aZDB-23-DGGb2007  aZDB-23-DLSc2000d2014